<h4>
    Dimensional Analysis
</h4>

<p>
    When we do dimensional analysis in physics,
    we typically break formulas down to three unit:
    meters, kilograms, and seconds (also called MKS).
    When we do dimensional analysis on a function,
    we replace each quantity with the unit of that quantity in terms
    of meters, kilograms, and seconds.
</p>
<p>
   To complete a dimensional analysis, follow these steps:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Replace each quantity in the equation with its unit in terms
        of meters, kilograms, and seconds.
    </li>
    <li>
        Following the order of operations, any quantities raised
        to an exponent means you raise each unit to the same exponent.
    </li>
    <li>
        Any quantities being multiplied or divided, follow the
        laws of multiplying and dividing fractions.
        Typically, these results in many unit cancelling.
    </li>
    <li>
        Any quantities being added or subtracted <strong>must</strong>
        have the same unit. If so, then when doing dimensional
        analysis you can replace the added quantities as one quantity
        with the same unit.
    </li>
    <li>
        In the end, each term of the equation must have the same unit.
    </li>
</ul>
