<h4>
    Proportionality
</h4>

<p>
    There are two types of proportionality you see in the
    equations for energy:
    <strong>direct</strong> proportionality
    and <strong>square</strong> proportionality.
</p>

<p>
    Proportionality comes into play whenever
    you multiply or divide quantities by certain amounts.
    For example, when quantities are doubled, halved, tripled,
    quadrupled, or divided by nine.
    Proportionality is never used when adding or subtracting.
</p>

<p>
    When two quantities are directly proportional,
    whatever you do to one quantity you do to the other.
    For example, if A and B are directly proportional
    and B is doubled, then A is also doubled.
</p>

<p>
    If if one quantity is proportional to the square of another,
    then whenever the second quantity is multiplied or divided by some factor,
    you multiply or divide the first by the square of that factor.
    For example, if A is proportional to the square of
    B, and B is multiplied by 2,
    A is multiplied by 2<sup>2</sup>.
    If B is multiplied by 5, A is multiplied by 5<sup>2</sup>.
    If B is divided by 27, A is divided by 27<sup>2</sup>.
</p>

